# .trivyignore — Trivy misconfig scan suppressions
# Each entry maps to a documented architectural decision.
# Format: RULE-ID  # rationale
# See: https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/#trivyignore

# KSV014 — Container readOnlyRootFilesystem
# Nextcloud (PHP) and its backup/cron sidecar containers require writable
# filesystem paths: PHP session files, OPcache, app cache, Nextcloud upgrade
# scratch space, and pg_dump output. readOnlyRootFilesystem is explicitly set
# to false in values.yaml. tmpfs-based isolation is tracked as a hardening
# backlog item. Access is restricted by K8s RBAC + NetworkPolicy.
# Maps to: §3.7 Kubernetes securityContext — acknowledged, remediation deferred.
KSV014

# KSV117 — Container port < 1024 (privileged port)
# Nextcloud serves HTTP internally on port 80, which is standard for FPM-based
# web server containers. External access uses port 443 via the Ingress + cert-
# manager (TLS 1.3). The pod runs as non-root (UID 33 / www-data); kernel port
# restrictions inside the container namespace are not a security boundary here.
# Maps to: §3.7 Kubernetes — port 80 is the canonical Nextcloud container port.
KSV117

# KSV-0109 — ConfigMap stores secrets (key/value pattern match on "password")
# Two known false positives in this repository:
#   1. vaultwarden/helm/templates/configmap.yaml: PASSWORD_ITERATIONS (numeric
#      PBKDF2 iteration count, not a credential) and SHOW_PASSWORD_HINT (boolean
#      feature flag, not a credential). Moving these to a Secret would be
#      misleading — they are non-sensitive operational settings.
#   2. wordpress/helm/templates/mu-plugins-configmap.yaml: PHP source code that
#      assigns to $phpmailer->Password using a PHP constant (SMTP_PASS) read from
#      the environment at runtime. No credential value is stored in the ConfigMap.
# All actual credentials in this repo are managed via InfisicalSecret CRDs.
# Maps to: §3.1 PR.DS (Infisical for production secrets), §3.7 ConfigMap for
# non-secret config only — these suppressed entries comply with that convention.
# Note: AVD-KSV-0109 format is required for Trivy ≤0.55 (CI uses 0.53.0 via
# trivy-action v0.24.0); KSV-0109 works only in Trivy 0.60+.
AVD-KSV-0109

# ─── cluster-backup (Velero + restic) ───────────────────────────────────────
# A cluster-level backup tool inherently requires broad permissions over the
# resources it backs up and restores, plus host-level access for the restic
# node-agent. These suppressions are scoped to the cluster-backup chart only.
# Real RBAC tightening (removing pods/exec, dropping unnecessary verbs from
# the restic ClusterRole) has been done at the source — see
# cluster-backup/helm/templates/{restic,velero}-rbac.yaml.

# KSV-0041 — ClusterRole 'cluster-backup-velero' manages 'secrets'
# Velero MUST back up and restore Kubernetes Secrets — that is core
# disaster-recovery functionality. Removing this access would defeat the
# purpose of the tool. Scope is intentional: only the velero/restic
# ServiceAccounts are bound to this ClusterRole.
KSV-0041
AVD-KSV-0041

# KSV-0056 — ClusterRole 'cluster-backup-velero' manages networking resources
# Velero MUST back up and restore Services, Endpoints, Ingresses, and
# NetworkPolicies. Without this, restored workloads have no inbound traffic
# routing. Inherent to the tool's responsibility.
KSV-0056
AVD-KSV-0056

# KSV-0048 — ClusterRole 'cluster-backup-velero' manages workloads and pods
# Restoring a cluster means re-creating Deployments, StatefulSets, DaemonSets,
# Jobs, CronJobs, and the pods they own. Inherent.
KSV-0048
AVD-KSV-0048

# KSV-0049 — ClusterRole 'cluster-backup-velero' manages ConfigMaps
# ConfigMaps carry application configuration and MUST be backed up / restored
# for a meaningful DR posture. Inherent.
KSV-0049
AVD-KSV-0049

# KSV-0005 / KSV-0022 — restic container has SYS_ADMIN capability
# Velero's restic node-agent requires SYS_ADMIN to perform the mount/setns
# operations it uses while reading pod-volume contents through the kubelet
# bind-mount. This is the documented Velero v1.12 deployment posture
# (https://velero.io/docs/v1.12/restic/). The PSS for the `velero`
# namespace must be `baseline` or `privileged`, never `restricted`.
KSV-0005
AVD-KSV-0005
KSV-0022
AVD-KSV-0022

# KSV-0012 — restic container runs as root
# Same operational requirement as KSV-0005 above: restic must run as uid 0
# to read pod-volume contents owned by arbitrary uids through the kubelet
# bind-mount. See KSV-0005 rationale.
KSV-0012
AVD-KSV-0012

# KSV-0042 — ClusterRole 'cluster-backup-velero' deletes pods
# Velero restores cluster state by re-creating workloads, which involves
# deleting pre-existing pods that conflict with the restored manifests.
# Inherent to the restore operation.
KSV-0042
AVD-KSV-0042

# KSV-0125 — Velero / restic container images come from docker.io
# `velero/velero:v1.12.2` is the upstream Velero project's official
# distribution. There is no published WeOwn / private-registry mirror;
# changing to a different registry would require self-hosting the image.
# Tracked as a follow-up if the team decides to mirror Velero internally.
KSV-0125
AVD-KSV-0125

# KSV-0023 — restic DaemonSet uses hostPath
# Restic mounts the kubelet pod-volume root (`/var/lib/kubelet/pods`) from
# the host so it can read other pods' on-disk state without invoking exec
# into them. This is the ONLY way Velero's pod-volume backup mechanism
# works; removing the hostPath would disable restic backups entirely.
# The mount is intentionally scoped to ONLY `/var/lib/kubelet/pods` — the
# earlier version of the chart mounted host `/`, which has been removed.
KSV-0023
AVD-KSV-0023
